  The `job[0m[2m_queue.py` file reveals the root cause of the duplicate processing issue.[0m[2m The `dequeue` method iterates through `_jobs.values()` and returns the *first pending job it finds*. The `asyncio.sleep(0.01)` inside the loop, combined with multiple workers calling `dequeue` concurrently, creates[0m[2m a race condition. Multiple workers can read the same job as "pending" before any single worker has a chance to update its status to "processing".
     
     To fix this, the `dequeue` method needs to ensure that only one worker can pick[0m[2m up a job at a time. This can be achieved by using an `asyncio.Lock` to protect the job status update.
     
